truth (keep, verified accurate): "Stop relying solely on programmatic permission checks like checkCallingOrSelfPermission; enforce the same custom permissions in the AndroidManifest.xml file. If you also add a programmatic check as defense-in-depth, it must fail closed (return/throw on denial) — logging and falling through is worse than no check at all."

code_bad (unchanged, still a fair negative example — fails open on log-only... but actually keep as illustrating "programmatic-only, no manifest backing"):
  int canProcess = checkCallingOrSelfPermission("com.example.perm.READ_INCOMING_MSG");
  if (canProcess != PERMISSION_GRANTED) throw new SecurityException();
  // still not recommended as the SOLE control -- no manifest enforcement shown

code_good (replace — show the actual OWASP-recommended fix, manifest enforcement, from the same MASTG page's "Custom Permissions" implementation example):
  <!-- AndroidManifest.xml -->
  <permission android:name="com.example.myapp.permission.START_MAIN_ACTIVITY"
      android:label="Start Activity in myapp"
      android:protectionLevel="signature" />
  <activity android:name=".SecureActivity"
      android:permission="com.example.myapp.permission.START_MAIN_ACTIVITY" />

  // optional defense-in-depth check -- must fail CLOSED, not just log:
  if (ContextCompat.checkSelfPermission(this, "com.example.myapp.permission.START_MAIN_ACTIVITY")
          != PackageManager.PERMISSION_GRANTED) {
      throw new SecurityException("Permission denied");
  }

source note to attach: the ContextCompat.checkSelfPermission Log.v-only snippet in MASTG-TEST-0024 is OWASP's audit cue ("whenever you see code like this, verify manifest enforcement exists"), not a secure reference implementation — do not extract it as code_good verbatim again.

